<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Retaliation Against U.S. for Flight Refusal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803084094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1803084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. Department of Transportation has refused 
to allow the Japan Air Lines to inaugurate a regular 
Sendai-Honolulu flight. Commenting on the refusal by the U.S. 
Department of Transport at a news conference on 17 March, 
Michihiko Matsuo, administrative vice minister of the Transport 
Ministry, criticized the U.S. Department of Transportation, 
saying, "Japan has the right to ask the United States to allow 
the inauguration of such a new regular flight for the Japanese 
airline in accordance with the Japan-U.S. Aviation Agreement." 
As for Japan's countermeasures, including restrictions on 
flights by American airlines to Japan, he said, "What we have to 
do first is to continue to ask the United States to go along 
with our request for opening the regular flight." In this way, 
he made clear that Japan will not think of taking any 
countermeasures against the United States for the time being. 
  The Japan Air Lines planned to inaugurate its first 
Sendai-Honolulu regular flight on 17 March, but it hurriedly 
shifted to a charter flight. The chartered airliner with 275 
passengers aboard left Sendai for Honolulu on the evening of 17 
March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6439 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas053__a94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-053-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

