<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deregulation Measures Said Unlikely Until Jun </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603050994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 16 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1603050994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 16 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of international trade and 
industry, when asked about reports that the United States wants 
Japan to ease 45 instances of regulations, admitted, "I 
understand that such a request came in January in addition to 
the three priority areas in the Japanese-U.S. economic framework 
talks." Talking to reporters following a cabinet meeting on 15 
March, Kumagai then said, "It will be impossible to finalize 
deregulation issues by the end of March; it will probably take 
until the end of June to resolve them." 
  As for the direction of future tax cuts and financial 
resources to cover the resulting shortfalls in revenue, which 
are the issues that the United States is concerned about, the 
minister said: "Because the matter will have an impact on the 
formulation of the 1995 budget, we must arrive at a conclusion 
on it by the end of June. I am shocked by the thinking of some 
people who believe that this matter can be put off." The 
minister insisted that the matter should be settled by the time 
of the [Naples G-7] summit, and he served a warning to the 
members of the Social Democratic Party of Japan and others who 
are indecisive about the tax-cut question. 

</TEXT>

