<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visual Information Market Growth Forecast </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803004394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1803004394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The New Visual Information Industry Panel has 
compiled a report forecasting the future of the visual and 
multimedia information industry. The Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry [MITI] adopted the report at a meeting of the 
panel on 16 March. 
  The panel is a private panel for the chief of the MITI 
Industry Policy Bureau. The report, pointing to the drastically 
growing demand for visual information in the individual 
entertainment and office work sectors, estimates the visual 
information market will grow from 15 trillion yen in 1992 to 71 
trillion in 2015. The report points out that for the market to 
expand in the future, it is important to deregulate and upgrade 
the current information and communications infrastructures and 
to establish an intellectual property rights system to protect 
copyrights. 
  Visual information uses computers to transmit images and 
sounds to the human visual and auditory senses. For this reason, 
the report predicts that visual information will make it easy to 
get information, and the demand for visual information will grow 
drastically, especially in the exchange of information between 
individuals and enterprises. The report analyzes that the demand 
for information in the medical, education, and distribution 
sectors will grow. 
  The report estimates the visual information market will grow 
from 15 trillion yen (3.2 percent of the GNP) in 1992 to 25 
trillion yen (4.2 percent of GNP) in 2000, and to 71 trillion 
yen (8.3 percent of GNP) in 2015. The report points out that for 
the visual information industry to develop in the future, it is 
necessary to upgrade the current infrastructure, create an 
information and communications network, establish a center where 
visual information is stored and utilized, and establish a 
visual information industry complex where related industries are 
concentrated. The report advocates the need to provide financial 
assistance to entrepreneurs eager to participate in the visual 
information industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

