<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Threatens Hardline Policy Toward North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1803024994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0200 GMT 18 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1803024994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the belief that it is now time to basically 
reexamine its policy on the North Korean nuclear problem, the 
government plans to adopt hardline policies, including the 
resumption of the Team Spirit exercise, if North Korea does not 
show a change in its attitude by 21 March. 
  Chong Chong-uk, senior presidential secretary for diplomatic 
and security affairs, pointed out today that progress in the 
North Korean nuclear issue up to now has been very 
unsatisfactory and the possibility of this issue being turned 
over to the UN Security Council is highly likely. He noted that 
the government is being forced to basically reexamine its 
previous policies, thus expressing serious concern over this 
situation. 
  However, Senior Secretary Chong Chong-uk said that the 
governments of the ROK and the United States are making 
last-stage efforts in various ways to make North Korea fulfill 
the agreement reached between the United States and North Korea, 
including sincere acceptance of inspection and the exchange of 
North-South special envoys. He noted that he has not discarded 
the hope for a peaceful solution to the problem. 
  Senior Secretary Chong Chong-uk revealed that the government 
will finalize its position after watching the special meeting of 
the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] Board of Governors 
slated for 21 March and a North-South working-level contact 
slated for 19 March. He pointed out that in the event that the 
special Board of Governors meeting concludes that the nuclear 
inspection ended in failure and that no progress is made in the 
issue of exchanging special envoys, resumption of the Team 
Spirit exercise and introduction of Patriot missiles will be 
inevitable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

