<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Zarubino Port Seeks Corporate Investors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703013994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0116 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703013994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- Zarubino port 
authorities in Maritime Province, Russia, have contacted major 
Korean companies about a port-development project worth 500 to 
600 million U.S. dollars, industry sources said Thursday. 
  The head of Khasan district, Anatoly Melnichenko, and the 
director-general of Khasansky Sea commercial port visited the 
Maritime and Port Administration (MAPA) Thursday to discuss 
opening a sea route between Sokcho, a northeastern port here, 
and Zarubino. 
  The Russians said they wanted to improve the port facilities 
independently from the central government in Moscow and are 
therefore negotiating with neighboring countries such as South 
Korea and Japan to attract foreign investment. 
  They proposed creating joint-venture companies to major 
business groups here such as Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo and Hanbo 
and received a positive response, the Russians said. 
  Zarubino was developed as a fishing port and administered by 
the central government before the Soviet Union collapsed in 
1991, but administrative power has since been handed over to the 
private sector. 
  Zarubino is located 70 km from the Chinese city of Hunchun, 
which was selected as a key area under the Tumen River 
development plan sponsored by the United Nations Development 
Program (UNDP) in 1991. 
  If its facilities are modernized, Zarubino Port will thus be 
in a good position to link North Korea, China and Russia in a 
day's time, the Russians said. 
  Zarubino port can currently handle four 20,000-ton-class 
ships at a time, but it plans to build a 1.9-km quay for six 
ships. 
  The port also aims to construct loading facilities and to 
improve rail links with the Trans-Siberian railroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

