<H3> <TI>   Swedish Navy Ship Visits To Promote Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703060294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0230 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703060294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Inchon, South Korea, March 17 (YONHAP) -- The 
Swedish mine-laying ship "Carlskrona" put in at Inchon port on 
Thursday, with 154 Swedish Naval Academy students and crew 
aboard. 
  The 3,300-ton mine layer, which boasts the latest weapons, 
shooting control equipment and advanced navigation system, left 
Sweden on Jan. 4 for a round-the-world trip and has visited 
Morocco, Hawaii and Japan, crossing the Atlantic and Pacific 
Oceans. 
  Carlskrona, the first Swedish Navy vessel to stop in South 
Korea, is expected to help promote bilateral relations. 
  The students and navy men plan to visit the truce village of 
Panmunjom, folk village in Yong-in and other major historical 
sites before sailing for Hong Kong. 
  The ship will also visit Bangkok, Malaysia, India, Pakistan, 
Turkey and Spain before returning to Sweden in May. 

</TEXT>

