<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Peacekeeping Unit Returns From Somalia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703072294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0614 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703072294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- The 250-man South Korean 
peacekeeping mission to Somalia returns home Friday morning 
after carrying out eight months of road construction and repair 
work in the strife-torn African nation. 
  The "Evergreen" Army engineering unit will be welcomed at an 
official ceremony in the afternoon by Defense Minister Yi 
Pyong-tae and 2,000 other officers and family members. 
  The unit marked South Korea's first participation in U.N. 
peacekeeping operations. It arrived in Somalia last July and 
was to stay one full year but decided to follow Western nations 
including Italy, which was in charge of security in the area 
where the Korean unit was stationed, and pull out early. 
  The South Korean soldiers were to leave Somalia on April 1 
but pushed up the date because of an outbreak of endemic 
diseases such as cholera, officials here said. 
  Some 500,000 U.S. dollars' worth of equipment including 
jeeps 
and electric generators was donated to the U.N. mission 
headquarters as the South Korean unit departed from the Somali 
capital of Mogadishu on Wednesday. 
  Other equipment left Mogadishu on Monday aboard a 5,500-ton 
German vessel and will arrive in the southern port city of Pusan 
around April 10. 
  The United Nations will pay the entire 800-million-won cost 
of transporting the unit and equipment. 

</TEXT>

