<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jan-Feb Electronics Exports Rise 50 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703051994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0221 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703051994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- Electronics exports 
surged more than 50 percent in the first two months of this year 
over 1993 due to better quality and a strong Japanese yen, 
industry sources said Thursday. 
  Samsung Electronics Co. recorded exports of 1.35 billion 
U.S. 
dollars in January-February, up 50 percent from 900 million 
dollars last year. 
  Exports of electronic equipment, including semiconductors, 
surged 58 percent to 630 million dollars from 400 million 
dollars. 
  Goldstar Co. saw exports rise 32 percent to 500 million 
dollars in the two months. 
  Exports to Asia soared 67 percent to 150 million dollars 
while new target areas -- the Middle East and Africa -- 
accounted for a 60-percent rise. 
  Daewoo Electronics Co. enjoyed a leap of 57 percent in 
January-February exports to 340 million dollars. Shipments of 
washing machines and refrigerators skyrocketed 103 percent and 
78 percent, respectively. 
  Growth in exports to the Commonwealth of Independent States 
and Latin America was most evident, Daewoo officials said. 
  Should the trend continue, Korean electronics exports may 
reach 30 billion dollars, up 3.5 billion dollars from the 
initial target of 26.5 billion dollars. 

</TEXT>

