<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii Suspected of Violating U.S. Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803101494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1006 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii attended a meeting of his supporters at a U.S. military 
base last month, raising suspicion of violating a Japan-U.S. 
military agreement, political sources said Friday [18 March]. 
  Fujii, a member of Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party) in the 
governing coalition, was present at a general meeting of his 
supporters held February 20 at the U.S. base at Atsugi in the 
suburbs of Tokyo, the sources said. 
  They said the use of a U.S. military base by ordinary 
Japanese citizens is banned in principle under the Status of 
Forces Agreement between Japan and the United States. 
  Fujii told reporters he understood that the meeting was 
aimed 
at promoting friendship between U.S. forces and local 
residents, and therefore did not constitute a violation of the 
agreement. 
  Foreign Ministry officials said they were not sure if the 
U.S. side regarded the meeting as part of political activities, 
but added that the ministry will ask the U.S. military to be 
careful about offering its facilities for use by Japanese 
citizens. 
  The sources said about 300 members of the supporting group, 
including the mayor of Yamato, where the base is located, and 
members of the city's assembly, attended. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6521 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas053_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-053 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Views U.S. Demand on Base Bid Rigging </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703153794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1457 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- The United States 
Government on Thursday [17 March] submitted its demand that 70 
Japanese construction and other firms pay more than 1.1 billion 
yen in penalties for rigging bids on construction projects at a 
U.S. naval air station southwest of Tokyo. 
  According to the notices, the firms inflated contract fees 
for the construction projects from 1984 to 1990 through a 
constructors' group at the U.S. naval station at Atsugi, 
Kanagawa Prefecture. 
  If the named firms, which include the Maeda Corp., 
Nishimatsu 
Construction Co. and Tokyu Construction Co., do not reply in 10 
days, the demands will be filed as a suit in court, the notices 
said. 
  The notices allege that the group engaged in illegal trade 
activities that injured the United States. 
  The president of the Japan Federation of Construction 
Contractors (JFCC), Kenji Maeda, remarked "there is no evidence 
of bid-rigging, because no orders were received." 
  "The talks among contracters that were indicated was to 
administer quality," said Maeda, who also heads the Maeda 
construction firm. 

</TEXT>

