<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, EU Remain Apart on Auto Export Quotas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703142994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1414 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Japan and Europe remained 
split over quota of Japanese auto exports to the European Union 
(EU) for 1994 at the first day of two-day talks on Thursday [17 
March], Japanese negotiators said. 
  Japan sought an increase while the EU asserted that the 
quota 
should be unchanged from 1993. 
  In 1993, both sides agreed to cut Japan's exports by 18.5 
percent from the previous year to 980,000 vehicles in light of 
slumping demand in Europe. 
  They will try again to reach an agreement Friday, the second 
day of the bilateral talks at the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry (MITI), according to the negotiators. 

</TEXT>

