<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Concerned About DPRK Nuclear Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803081494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0756 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803081494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Friday voiced renewed concern about North Korea's 
alleged nuclear weapons development program, a Foreign Ministry 
official said. 
  "In this (Asia-Pacific) region, a series of favorable 
developments can be seen after the end of the Cold War, but 
there are some destabilizing factors such as North Korea's 
nuclear (program)," the official quoted the premier as saying in 
an interview with journalists from China. 
  North Korea is suspected of producing nuclear weapons at its 
facilities in Yongbyon, about 90 kilometers north of Pyongyang. 
It has refused to permit the International Atomic Energy 
Agency, the Vienna-based international nuclear watchdog, to 
conduct checks at a nuclear site. 
  The interview, held at the premier's official residence for 
nearly an hour, came a day before Hosokawa begins an official 
three- day visit to China. During his stay, he will meet with 
Chinese Premier Li Peng and other leaders in Beijing and make 
inspections of an economic development zone in Shanghai. 
  Hosokawa expressed hope to reaffirm with Chinese leaders the 
shared view that Tokyo and Beijing should further enhance their 
ties so that together they can contribute to the international 
community, the official said. 
  "I wish to have a meaningful and candid exchange of views 
with them to further promote Japan-China ties toward the 21st 
century," he reportedly said. 
  Touching on expanding bilateral trade and growing Japanese 
investment in China, Hosokawa also told the Chinese reporters 
that the prospects for Japan-China economic and trade relations 
are bright. 

</TEXT>

