<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Extend Aid to Former Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803071894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0636 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- Japan will extend a total 
of 8.2 million dollars to international humanitarian 
organizations to help the people afflicted in the conflicts in 
the former Yugoslavia, the Foreign Ministry said Friday [18 
March]. 
  Of the total, Japan will extend the World Health 
Organization 
(WHO) 3 million dollars for providing medicine and medical 
supplies, and 700,000 dollars to the U.N. Industrial Development 
Organization (UNIDO) for repairing the existing facilities to 
accommodate displaced people, the ministry said. 
  The assistance also includes 3 million Swiss francs, or 
about 
2 million dollars, to the International Committee for the Red 
Cross (ICRC) to provide safe water and medical equipment, and 
2.5 million dollars to the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF) for 
providing educational material and equipment, it said. 
  The latest aid brought the total amount of Japanese 
assistance to the people in the former Yugoslavia to 14.7 
million dollars. 
  Since the outbreak of conflict in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 
March 1992, about 4.2 million people have been afflicted and are 
facing a serious lack of food and daily necessities, according 
to the ministry. 

</TEXT>

