<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Suspends New Economic Aid to Nigeria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803105494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1030 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- The government announced 
Friday [18 March] it is suspending new economic aid to Nigeria, 
which has been under military rule since last November. 
  Nigeria is not eligible for Japan's official development 
assistance (ODA) since the regime has dissolved the parliament, 
banned political rallies and taken other undemocratic measures, 
government officials said. 
  Japan, however, will continue to provide emergency 
humanitarian aid to the west African country, they said. 
  Japan will resume aid when Nigeria restores civilian rule, 
the officials said. 
  By fiscal 1992, Japan had provided 87.4 billion yen in 
yen-based loans to Nigeria, the second largest amount it had 
given an African nation, next to Kenya. 

</TEXT>

