<H3> <TI>   Market-Opening Steps `Should Include' Tax Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803035094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0218 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803035094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- Japan should include 
macroeconomic steps, including permanent tax cuts, in 
market-opening measures due this month, economic planning chief 
Manae Kubota said Friday [18 March]. 
  "The direction should be indicated as concretely as 
possible," Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning 
Agency (EPA), told a regular news conference after a morning 
cabinet meeting. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa urged ministers concerned 
to 
work harder in the macroeconomic field, she said. 
  Kubota said tax cuts, expansion of domestic demand and 
cutting the current account surplus need further discussion. 
  The coalition government has already vowed to enact 
permanent 
tax reform this year, which is expected to offset reductions of 
income tax and other taxes by hiking the consumption tax. 
  The reform is seen as answering U.S. complaints that this 
year's 6 trillion yen in income and resident's tax cuts are just 
one-time measures and will not give domestic demand the 
sustained boost needed to help cut Japan's trade surplus. 
  Suggestions have emerged in recent days to include such 
macroeconomic steps in the market-opening package due by month's 
end, which is to include deregulation, import promotion, 
stricter antitrust enforcement and improved government 
procurement practices. 

</TEXT>

