<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Han, Christopher Hold `Emergency' Teleconference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1803025994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0210 GMT 18 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1803025994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In an emergency telephone conversation, Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu and U.S. Secretary of State Christopher 
shared the view [insigul kachihada] that the efforts of the two 
countries to solve the North Korean nuclear issue have reached 
an important stage. They discussed measures to take henceforth. 
  Minister Han and Secretary Christopher agreed that the 
nuclear inspection by the International Atomic Energy Agency 
[IAEA] was not satisfactory [sunjoropchi mottaha] and no 
progress was made in the issue of exchanging North-South special 
envoys. As the result, a third round of U.S.-North Korea talks 
is undecided. 
  The foreign ministers of the two countries shared the view 
that the two countries will make last-ditch efforts for dialogue 
to persuade North Korea but will seek new measures -- 
omni-directional -- if the efforts for dialogue are not 
successful. 
  The ministers of the two countries agreed that it is 
important for the two countries to implement consistent measures 
at this point under close mutual consultations. 
  In the conversation, Minister Han revealed that during 
President Kim Yong-sam's visit to China beginning 26 March, the 
North Korean nuclear issue will be discussed at a ROK-PRC summit 
and in other occasions of consultation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

