<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Sees DPRK Sanctions as Nearly `Inevitable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1803005694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0039 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1803005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 (YONHAP) -- South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam voiced concern Thursday that international 
sanctions against North Korea could be inevitable due to the 
current nuclear row. 
  "It's a serious problem for the international community and 
truly unfortunate that the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) inspection in North Korea was incomplete, and that it was 
unable to inspect two important sites," Kim said in an interview 
with NHK-TV broadcast here on the evening news. 
  "It's now heading toward a situation where international 
sanctions cannot but be imposed on North Korea," he said. 
  The comments by South Korea's top executive came just hours 
after the IAEA announced in Vienna that its inspectors, during 
their two-week stay in North Korea, were denied access to 
important sites that could determine whether the Stalinist state 
diverted nuclear material for non-peaceful uses. 
  Kim's interview came a week before he heads to Tokyo on his 
first outing this year. It was only last year that the Seoul 
Government closed the book on the dark past with Tokyo from the 
1910-45 colonial years. 
  On opening his country to Japanese cultural imports, Kim 
said 
the important thing is to open up naturally and gradually 
through exchanges between the two peoples and their governments. 
  "The opening will have to wait until such time comes," he 
said, predicting that this would occur during the remaining four 
years of his presidency. 
  He also thought a visit to Korea by Japanese Emperor Akihito 
was possible during the next four years, a step officials here 
say is the last emotional door to close on the two countries' 
past relations. 
  But it's important to create an atmosphere where the people 
of both countries can sincerely welcome such a visit, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

