<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujii Arrives for Finance Talks </H4>
<F P=102> OW1903000594 Tokyo KYODO in English 2321 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903000594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Honolulu, March 18 KYODO -- Japan's Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii on Friday [18 March] called for a cautious and 
balanced approach in liberalizing financial markets in the 
Asia-Pacific region. "Too much impatience won't be good," Fujii 
said as he arrived in Honolulu for the finance ministers meeting 
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum. 
  Fujii said open financial markets are important for the 
region but policy-makers should take economic realities into 
consideration in opening up their markets. "We have to take 
into account the matter of soundness. We should proceed in a 
balanced manner," Fujii told reporters on arrival in Honolulu. 
  Fujii said he plans to talk about "the Japanese experience" 
during the two-day APEC meeting and underscore the importance of 
cooperation in the regional group. The meeting, which opens 
with an informal reception Friday evening, is expected to focus 
on ways to promote economic growth and foster the flow of 
capital in the Asia-Pacific region. 
  Fujii has a series of separate meetings planned with his 
APEC 
counterparts Friday afternoon, including a bilateral session 
with U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen, Japanese officials 
said. 
  Fujii is also scheduled to meet with Chinese Finance 
Minister 
Liu Zhongli, Australian Finance Minister Ralph Willis and 
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Ibrahim 
Anwar. 

</TEXT>

