<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Human Rights Policy Criticized </H4>
<F P=102> OW1903101394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0932 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Honolulu, March 18 KYODO -- Malaysian Deputy Prime 
Minister Anwar Ibrahim blasted the United States Friday [18 
March] over its human rights policy toward China, accusing 
Washington of forcing its values "down the throat" of other 
countries. "To assume that we have the sole monopoly in our 
understanding of democracy and human rights constitutes a form 
of arrogance," Anwar said. 
  Anwar, who was in Honolulu for an Asia-Pacific finance 
ministers meeting, said he raised Malaysia's concern of the U.S. 
human rights policy in a meeting with U.S. Treasury Secretary 
Lloyd Bentsen. Anwar was particularly critical of the U.S. 
policy of linking China's human rights record to its most 
favored nation trading status in the United States. 
  Linking trade issues with human rights amounts to "forc(ing) 
down the throat of other countries to see your point of view," 
Anwar said. 
  Anwar, who serves as Malaysia's finance minister, said the 
United States should "listen a bit more" on political realities 
in other countries. When it comes to human rights, "you must 
show a lot of tolerance and understanding," Anwar said. 

</TEXT>

