<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bentsen, Fujii Focus on Region </H4>
<F P=102> OW2003072994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0717 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003072994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Honolulu, March 19 KYODO -- U.S. Treasury Secretary 
Lloyd Bentsen and Japan's Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii set 
aside bilateral bickerings on trade Saturday and focused their 
attention on regional issues of high finance instead. 
  The two ministers shared the same roof for two days in a 
beachside Honolulu hotel but spent most of the time conferring 
with their counterparts from the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum. No bilateral issues were taken up, 
Japanese and U.S. officials said. 
  Bentsen and Fujii met one-on-one Friday but chose to skip 
issues on bilateral trade. "We came here for the APEC meeting," 
Fujii explained. 
  Yet the shadow of trade disputes loomed every time Bentsen 
and Fujii faced reporters. 
  How would frictions in U.S.-Japan relations affect the two 
countries' efforts to build a bridge with other nations in the 
Asia-Pacific region? That was the first question Bentsen faced 
at a joint news conference after the APEC conference was over. 
  Bentsen put up an air of optimism, not only on U.S. 
frictions 
with Japan but also with China. "I am optimistic that we're 
going to work these types of concerns out," Bentsen said. 
  On Japan, Bentsen said the United States is working to see 
what can be done. 
  "We're hopeful that will work out. I think that will be for 
the betterment of all of us," Bentsen said. 
  Fujii, who stood alongside 16 APEC ministers behind Bentsen 
at the joint news conference, took no initiative to offer his 
own views on the subject. When pressed on that point at a 
separate news conference later on, Fujii again offered no fresh 
insight. 
  Fujii reiterated that the meeting in Hawaii was about APEC, 
and not on U.S.-Japan frictions. "We would like to settle 
Japan-U.S. issues in a cooperative spirit," Fujii said. 

</TEXT>

