<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujii Promises Financial Support </H4>
<F P=102> OW2003032294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0253 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003032294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Honolulu, March 19 KYODO -- Japan on Saturday urged 
Pacific Rim countries to put more of their income into savings, 
build up the private sector, and step up the development of 
human resources, saying this is the secret of its rapid economic 
development since World War II. 
  Japanese Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii offered the 
triple-dose prescription for economic growth at the first 
finance ministers' meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum in Honolulu. "With a sound 
macroeconomic policy, it is important to strengthen domestic 
savings, strengthen the private sector and improve human 
resources," Fujii told his APEC colleagues. 
  Fujii also promised Japan's financial support, both through 
bilateral and multilateral channels, to help the developing 
nations in the APEC group. 
  Japanese officials said there was strong interest among APEC 
ministers in the Japanese model of economic development. "We 
are pleased that we got this kind of attention from our APEC 
partners," one Japanese official said. 
  Fujii said Japan's high rate of capital formation has been 
backed by a high rate of savings among the Japanese people. 
Research and development done by the private sector has also 
contributed to the success of product development among Japanese 
firms, he said. 

</TEXT>

