<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujii on APEC Market Development </H4>
<F P=102> OW2003065394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0637 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003065394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Honolulu, March 19 KYODO -- Japanese Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii stressed Saturday [19 March] the 
importance of developing capital markets in the nations of the 
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum. 
  Fujii, speaking at a press conference after a two-day 
meeting 
of APEC finance ministers here, gave high credits to the 
gathering but reserved his comments on making it a regular one. 
"It is first necessary to create an environment that 
facilitates flow of private funds in the APEC nations which has 
become a world growth center," Fujii said. 
  In a joint statement issued at the end of the conference, 
the 
17 APEC ministers agreed to develop their capital markets and 
improve capital flows as their principles of policy formation in 
the region. Praising the first-ever gathering of the APEC 
finance ministers, Fujii said, "we were able to learn together 
with (other APEC) nations that are continuing to stage diverse 
(economic) growth." 
  Fujii confirmed that the ministers agreed to meet again next 
year in Indonesia but he showed a negative stance on holding it 
regularly. "It moves under the atmosphere at that time." 
  Meanwhile, Japanese officials quoted Fujii as saying at the 
meeting that the APEC nations must pursue "sound macroeconomic 
policy primarily to raise domestic savings to maintain high 
economic growth." They also said Fujii offered financial 
support both bilaterally and multilaterally to other APEC 
nations. 
  APEC groups the United States, Japan, Canada, China, Taiwan, 
Hong Kong, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, Singapore, 
Thailand, Malaysia, the Philippines, Indonesia, Brunei, Mexico 
and Papua New Guinea. Chile was also represented at the Hawaii 
meeting as it is due to join the APEC forum this fall. 

</TEXT>

