<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Held in Hawaii </TI></H3>
<H4>   1995 Meeting Set for Indonesia </H4>
<F P=102> OW2003050394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0435 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003050394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Antonio Kamiya] </F>
  [Excerpt] Honolulu, March 19 KYODO -- Finance ministers 
from the Asia-Pacific region Saturday [19 March] concluded a 
two-day conference with a pledge to work toward freer capital 
flow in the region. The ministers from the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum also agreed to review progress 
of their work in another joint APEC conference to be held next 
year in Indonesia. 
  "I have made numerous new friends this weekend (and) we have 
established new relationships that each of us can build on," 
U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen said in announcing the 
conclusion of the first APEC finance ministers conference. 
Bentsen, who hosted the two-day event, sounded upbeat about 
what he called a "congenial" meeting of the minds among the 18 
Pacific Rim ministers who attended the conference at a scenic 
beachside hotel on this resort island. 
  Japan's Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii also echoed 
Bentsen's 
sentiment. It is most gratifying that we are able to conclude 
the meeting in this manner, Fujii told reporters. 
  Growing tension in the U.S. trade relations with China and 
Japan did not appear to dilute the jovial, informal atmosphere 
of an outdoor joint news conference. 
  "I am optimistic to work this type of concern out," Bentsen 
said when asked about China's threatened "most-favored-nation" 
(MFN) trade status with the United States. Bentsen also said 
the U.S. is likewise "hopeful" of working out its trade disputes 
with Japan. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

