<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   KYODO on Talks Breakdown </H4>
<F P=102> OW1903032894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0252 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903032894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 19 KYODO -- The eighth round of 
working- level talks to discuss procedures for an inter-Korean 
exchange of special envoys between Seoul and Pyongyang broke 
down Saturday [19 March], government officials said. 
  The 55-minute meeting at the truce border village of 
Panmunjom ended without setting a date for the next round of 
talks. The talks collapsed with North Korean negotiators 
walking away from the dialogue table, the officials said. 
  The South Korean side urged North Korea to drop 
"unreasonable" demands and show sincerity in its attitude to 
make improvements in working through differences over procedural 
matters, they said. 
  Song Chung-tae, the chief South Korean delegate to the 
inter-Korean dialogue, sounded out a tough warning that the 
nuclear issue is entering a critical phase, with the 
international community considering punitive actions at some 
point. 
  "Time is quickly running out and it is hard to tell what 
ominous consequences North Korea's recalcitrance on the nuclear 
issue will bring about," Song said. 
  In response to Song's remarks, his northern counterpart Pak 
Yong-su raised his country's earlier demands and accused South 
Korea of using the inter-Korean contact as a way to scuttle 
high-level talks between the United States and North Korea. 
  Pak blamed South Korean's uncooperative acts for failing to 
make significant progress in the inter-Korean dialogue for an 
exchange of special envoys. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

