<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   ROK Delegate Makes Statement </H4>
<F P=102> SK2103084894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0839 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 21 (YONHAP) -- South Korea warned North 
Korea on Monday that if it chooses a road other than dialogue, 
the South will react with full strength. 
  Song Yong-tae, the South's chief delegate to the 
just-suspended inter-Korean working-level talks, said in a 
statement that Seoul remains committed to resolving the North 
Korean nuclear dispute peacefully. 
  "The door to dialogue remains open. We strongly urge the 
North to return to a sincere and rightful posture and respond 
favorably to efforts to resume South-North dialogue, aware of 
the internal and external conditions that exist," Song said. 
  He said North Korea was amply demonstrating its bellicosity 
by resorting to Cold-War-type actions that fan confusion in the 
South, trying to subvert the South's system by slandering its 
top leader and agitating South Koreans to struggle against their 
government. 
  Song said that if Pyongyang is truly interested in holding 
talks with the United States, it should be more sincere in 
respecting international order and realizing the proposed 
exchange of special envoys. 
  He noted that the South had time and again shown its 
willingness to help the North improve relations with Seoul's 
allies if Pyongyang worked to resolve the nuclear issue. 
  North Korea is trying to blame the South for the recent 
breakdown of working-level talks in an attempt to escape 
international suspicions about its nuclear program, Song said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

