<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   21 Mar DPRK Statement Cited </H4>
<F P=102> SK2103022894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0212 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 21 (YONHAP) -- Pyongyang has sharply 
criticized Seoul for the rupture of inter-Korean talks on 
exchanging special envoys, saying the South would face "a curse 
and collapse for driving the state of affairs into a war 
situation." 
  In a statement issued Monday [21 March] on the breakdown of 
the eighth round of working-level talks at the weekend, the 
North Korean delegation said it had done everything possible to 
ensure the negotiations' success since offering to exchange 
special envoys last may, radio Pyongyang reported. 
  But the South hindered the cross-visits by erecting 
artificial barriers and the proposed exchange "now faces a grave 
crisis," the report quoted the statement as saying. 
  "While the dialogue was under way, the South took reckless 
actions threatening its dialogue partner, such as the 
maintenance of international cooperation (in dealing with the 
North Korean nuclear issue), war games including the Team Spirit 
military exercise with the United States and an attempt to 
deploy Patriot anti-missile missiles." 
  On the hard-line measures being considered by Seoul after 
the 
breakdown of inter-Korean dialogue, the statement called them 
"de facto declarations on destroying and renouncing the special 
envoy exchange and on an all-out confrontation." 
  It went on to say, "the measures have revealed the South's 
hidden schemes to make use of the inter-Korean dialogue in 
applying a brake to the North Korea-U.S. talks and to cease 
relations with the North, while driving the North-South 
relationship into a situation of confrontation and war." 
  "We will take note of the chief South Korean delegate's 
public statement that the South will no longer talk with the 
North," it added. 

</TEXT>

