<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   DPRK Ministry Statement Cited </H4>
<F P=102> SK2103031494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0303 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103031494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 21 (YONHAP) -- North Korea announced 
Monday that it has no choice but to withdraw from the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) should the United States resume 
the Team Spirit military exercise, and the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) further distort the results of inspections 
of North Korean nuclear sites and thus expand its "impartiality." 
  A North Korean Foreign Ministry statement monitored by 
NAEWOE 
press here said Pyongyang would not send a delegation to the 
third high-level meeting with the United States slated for 
Monday (Washington time). 
  "North Korea would find no other way but to translate into 
action the measures which were pronounced in its statement on 
March 12 (on withdrawal from the NPT) in order to defend the 
nation's right to independence and the security of the country" 
should the United States avoid high-level talks and resume Team 
Spirit, and the IAEA distort inspection results and expand 
impartiality, thereby stepping up its high-handedness and 
pressure on Pyongyang, NAEWOE, South Korea's observer of North 
Korean affairs, quoted the statement as saying. 
  The Foreign Ministry spokesman's statement, aired by the 
North Korean Central Broadcasting station and Radio Pyongyang, 
said North Korea would no longer feel obligated to guarantee the 
continuity of nuclear safeguards. 

</TEXT>

