<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputy Prime Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> SK1903073694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0700 GMT 19 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1903073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yi Yong-tok, deputy prime minister and minister of 
the National Unification Board, released a statement to the 
North this afternoon in connection with the breakup [kyollyol] 
of the eighth North-South working-level contact. In the 
statement, he said that North Korea's unilateral breakup of the 
working-level contact for the exchange of special envoys is an 
act of turning a blind eye to our efforts for dialogue for the 
resolution of the nuclear issue and the international efforts 
toward that end and that it is unacceptable and cannot be 
justified with any excuse. 
  In today's statement, Deputy Prime Minister Yi also said 
that 
contrary to our patient efforts, North Korea had consistently 
maintained an attitude of delaying or avoiding the adoption of 
the agreement for the exchange of special envoys and gone, 
finally, so far as to reject the contact itself, stating that it 
does not hesitate to wage a war. He also said that North Korea 
had been leading the situation to a serious phase. 
  He added that our position to peacefully resolve the nuclear 
issue remained unchanged and that the government would explore 
all means possible, while maintaining close international 
cooperation to resolve the nuclear issue. 
  He also urged North Korea to be keenly aware of the 
situation 
facing it at home and abroad at present and assume a correct 
attitude at an early date to resume the dialogue to resolve the 
nuclear issue. 

</TEXT>

