<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   Foreign Minister Cited on Exchange </H4>
<F P=102> SK1903075094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0736 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1903075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 19 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States agreed to push forward additional International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspections and inter-Korean 
exchange of special envoys, but refer the nuclear issue to the 
United Nations Security Council and hold the 1994 bilateral 
military exercise, "Team Spirit", if North Korea refuses to meet 
any of the two prerequisites, ruling Democratic Party (DP) chief 
policymaker Yi Se-ki said Saturday. 
  Yi said he was told by Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu over 
the 
telephone that Han and his U.S. counterpart Warren Christopher 
coordinated their position over the phone a day earlier. 
  If Pyongyang refuses any either of additional IAEA 
inspection 
or inter-Korean envoy exchange, the third-round high-level talks 
with Washington cannot take place and Team Spirit will be held 
this year, Han was quoted as saying. 
  Under such circumstance, North Korean nuclear problem will 
be 
inevitably referred to the Security Council, which likely will 
create tension in the Korean peninsula, Han told Yi. But Seoul 
and Washington will make efforts to persuade Pyongyang in 
agreeing to extra IAEA inspections and continue inter-Korean 
dialogue to realize envoy exchange, Han said. "It now looks like 
the (North Korean nuclear) problem has returned to the starting 
point and all channels blocked, but in the long run, there is 
room for hope if we continue dialogue," Han was quoted as saying. 
  Through dialogue efforts in the past year, North Korea has 
lost sympathy from the international community and Seoul and 
Washington have obtained sufficient grounds to persuade China to 
follow their steps in regards to possible decision by the 
Security Council, he said. 
  The government and DLP [Democratic Liberal Party] will meet 
next week to discuss the North Korean nuclear problem. 

</TEXT>

