<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Cited on Commitment to Country's Defense </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2103064994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0637 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 21 (YONHAP) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton sent a personal letter to South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam Monday, reaffirming the United States' commitment to 
defending South Korea as the North Korean nuclear dispute took a 
turn for the worse, presidential spokesman Chu Ton-sik said. 
  Kim received the letter from U.S. Ambassador to Seoul James 
Laney, who visited the president at Chongwadae [presidential 
offices] Monday morning shortly before Kim convened a meeting of 
security-related ministers, Chu said. 
  In his letter, Clinton told Kim that the United States has 
the will and determination to honor its commitment to defend 
South Korea against any aggression or provocation. 
  In order to do so, America will strengthen the joint 
U.S.-South Korean defense posture, Clinton said. 
  Clinton also reaffirmed that the United States will carry 
out 
the security agreement reached with President Kim when the two 
leaders met in Washington last November. 
  Since North Korea has not been sincere in allowing outside 
inspection of its nuclear facilities and in its dialogue with 
the South, the Korean peninsula and the world have reached the 
point where peace and stability are seriously threatened, 
Clinton said. 
  The U.S. President proposed that Washington and Seoul 
continue strengthening close consultation between the two sides 
while maintaining their basic position calling for a peaceful 
resolution of the North Korean nuclear issue, Chu said. 
  In spite of North Korea's attempts to drive a wedge between 
Seoul and Washington, the United States will never allow any 
such maneuvering to harm its relationship with South Korea, 
Clinton noted. 
  The United States will deal firmly with any North Korean 
moves, Clinton said, and will honor its pledge to defend South 
Korea under any circumstances. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

