<DOCNO> FBIS3-6588 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas054_d_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Policy on DPRK `Weakened' by U.S. `Hawks' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2003051494 Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN in Korean 20 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK2003051494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Washington-based correspondent Yi Chong-yon: </F>
"U.S. View on North Korea"] 
  [Text] Since the working-level contact between the North 
and South Korea held in Panmunjom on 19 March for the exchange 
of special envoys was ruptured due to the North Korean side's 
rejection of negotiations, the call for hardline measures 
against North Korea which prevailed within the United States 
after the nuclear inspection by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] has become more fierce. Since the assessment was 
put forward last week noting that the result of the IAEA's 
nuclear inspection of North Korea is not satisfactory, an 
alarming [simsangchi anta] and heated atmosphere began to take 
place within the United States. 
  In particular, as the IAEA notified the United States that 
it 
is going to convene a special meeting of its Board of Governors 
on 21 March to deal with the inspection of North Korean nuclear 
facilities by its inspection team, the United States, through a 
statement by the Department of State, revealed the possibility 
of the postponement or cancellation of the third round of North 
Korea-U.S. high-level talks slated for 21 March. 
  The U.S. Department of Defense also announced that it will 
discuss the issue of immediately resuming the ROK-U.S. joint 
military exercise by pointing out that the preconditions for the 
suspension of Team Spirit are the nuclear inspection and 
North-South high-level talks. 
  Realizing the seriousness of the situation, the White House 
reportedly plans to hold an emergency high-level meeting soon 
with participation by secretaries of state and defense, as well 
as assistants for security affairs. Meanwhile, President 
Clinton said that if North Korea does not accept complete 
nuclear inspection promptly, resumption of the ROK-U.S. joint 
military exercise and deployment of Patriot missiles to U.S. 
Forces Korea would be the means of choice. 
  Thus, a hardline trend against North Korea has been created 
within the United States since it was confirmed that the 
inspection activities of the IAEA inspection team were 
restricted by the North Korean authorities. 
  In particular, an unprecedentedly strong hardline air 
regarding North Korean problems is prevailing in the U.S. 
Congress. At present, the hawk faction regarding policy toward 
North Korea constitutes the main force both in the U.S. House of 
Representatives and the Senate. 
  It is a reality that the hardline stance against North Korea 
is becoming more fierce not only within the U.S. Congress but 
also in the Department of Defense whose hardline conservative 
nature has been traditionally strong. 
  In addition, the U.S. CIA is supplying various hawk faction 
members with intelligence materials that serve as the basis of 
the hardline stance against North Korea. 
  As a result of a hardline stance becoming superior, the 
position of the U.S. Department of State, which is the only 
organization within the Clinton administration calling for a 
solution of problems pertaining to North Korea through dialogue, 
has been weakened to a considerable extent. Up until 18 March, 
U.S. Secretary of State Christopher stressed that "nothing has 
been decided regarding the resumption of the Team Spirit 
exercise and a channel should be open for dialogue with North 
Korea even while working out measures for sanctions against it." 
  However, under the present situation in which the 
much-expected exchange of special envoys between the North and 
the South has clearly gone across the river, such an allegation 
for diplomatic solution by the State Department is being melted 
away [pichul ilta]. Therefore, it can be said that the North 
Korean nuclear issue is at a turning point from the U.S. 
argument between hardline and moderate factions into the phase 
of international sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6589 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas054_d_94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

