<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Western Source' Cited on Kim Il-song's Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2103104694 Seoul YONHAP in English 1040 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 21 (YONHAP) -- North Korea seems 
determined not to give up their nuclear efforts unless they are 
assured of ultimate diplomatic normalization with the United 
States and lift of the U.S.'s trade embargo on them, a Western 
source here who maintains close ties with Pyongyang said on 
Monday. 
  The source is one of the rare Western figures who have free 
access to Pyongyang and maintain close friendship with the 
Pyongyang leadership. 
  "At a recent high-level meeting presided over personally by 
Kim Il-song, North Korea reaffirmed their policy that they 
cannot abandon their nuclear efforts unless there are clear 
assurances from the United States for improved U.S.-North Korea 
relations with the ultimate recognition of North Korea by the 
United States, lift of the existing trade embargo and for 
economic support," the source said. 
  The source, whose latest visit to Pyongyang was timed with 
IAEA (International Atomic Energy Agency) inspectors' arrival in 
Pyongyang early this month, said he obtained the information 
from a ranking Pyongyang official with whom he has been on 
friendly terms. 
  "It is feared therefore that unless these basic conditions 
are met, tension could build up between South and North Korea 
over the nuclear issue," the source said. 
  He said that the United States in effect applies a rigid 
economic sanction against North Korea by limiting the amount of 
dollars carried by Korean-resident visitors to North Korea and 
banning trade with Pyongyang. 
  The source observed that it appears North Korea has turned 
more intransigent as the international community's call for 
thorough nuclear inspection had threatened to diminish chances 
for the effective use of their "nuclear card." 
  Until a while ago, North Korea planned to announce a limited 
opening if only there were a substantial progress in U.S.-North 
Korea relations such as the exchange of liaison offices, he 
added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

