<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kume Criticizes Kantor on Auto Parts Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903083694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1903083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association [JAMA] 
Chairman Yutaka Kume (concurrently chairman of Nissan Motor 
Corp.) stressed his position of not to completely follow the 
government's market opening package to be released later this 
month. At a news conference on 17 March, he referred to 
automakers' efforts to work out voluntary plans for expanding 
purchase of foreign-made auto and auto parts, and said: "Our 
import expansion plans are being discussed as voluntary efforts 
of the private sector. We want no comments from the 
government." His statement was made to check government 
officials' attempt to incorporate the purchase plan into their 
market opening package. At the same time, he severely 
criticized U.S. Trade Representative [USTR] Mickey Kantor's 
demand for the Japanese Government's guarantee for fulfilling 
parts purchasing targets, stressing the Kantor remark is "an 
attempt to ruin our efforts." 
  Japanese automakers, including Toyota and Nissan, are 
individually mapping out plans for purchasing foreign-made auto 
parts. Chairman Kume said the JAMA is "planning business talks 
with auto and auto parts manufacturers not only of the United 
States, but also of Europe and other countries." To demonstrate 
"the industrial circles' initiative," the automakers' import 
expansion plan is expected to be released before the 
government's package. 
  However, Chairman Kume noted "our plan is intended to assist 
foreign manufacturers, and it is not the JAMA's numerical 
target." Touching particularly on USTR Kantor's demand for the 
Japanese Government's guarantee for the amount of auto parts 
imports, Kume said: "That is a very improper remark which may 
ruin automakers' initiative to better the Japan-U.S. relations." 
  Expansion of Japanese automakers' purchase of foreign-made 
autos and auto parts is the focal point of the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks. In connection with this, some 
quarters in the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] say "automakers' voluntary efforts should be added to our 
offer to the United States." MITI Vice Minister Hideaki Kumano 
hinted on 17 March at possibilities of merging the JAMA's parts 
purchase plan into the government's market opening package, 
saying: "I do not know contents of the private sector's plan, 
but we are considering (if it should be incorporated in the 
government's package)." 
  Under such circumstances, the automakers are wary of their 
voluntary efforts becoming "the government's formal pledge." A 
top official of a major automaker expressed his deep-rooted 
concern, saying: "At last, figures will go out of our control, 
and the private sector will have to suffer from them." 
  Chairman Kume showed discord between the public and private 
sectors on this issue, stressing: "Since this is a voluntary 
effort of the industrial circles, the government's intervention 
would become an obstacle." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

