<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   EPA's Kubota Views Market-Opening Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903054694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 19 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1903054694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 18 March Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] Manae Kubota, director general of the Economic 
Planning Agency [EPA], in a news conference following a formal 
cabinet meeting on 18 March, revealed that Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura in an informal cabinet meeting 
earlier in the day had asked the agency to make "special 
efforts" to study including macroeconomic plans in the 
government's market-opening measures to be finalized by the end 
of March. Director General Kubota indicated that she was 
thinking in a forward-looking manner about the study on 
including macroeconomic plans, telling reporters, "We are now at 
a stage where we must come up with all possible alternatives." 
  Kubota did not speak plainly about the contents of the 
possible macroeconomic plans, but she noted, "the need for tax 
cuts and the expansion of domestic demand have been pointed out; 
of course, then there is the problem of the current-accounts 
surplus." Adding "I think we should discuss these things in a 
little more orderly manner," she indicated the likelihood that 
these issues will be considered as the plans. 

</TEXT>

