<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Algerian Economic Minister Views Debt Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603074694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 15 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1603074694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 15 March Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] In an interview given to a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 
reporter in Tokyo, Algerian Economic Minister Mourad Benachenhou 
commented on negotiations for deferring the repayment of debts 
worth $30 billion, which is his objective in his visit to Japan, 
saying: "Japan showed a favorable attitude at the talks." 
However, Benachenhou pointed out that the Algerian economy will 
be faced with difficulties in the future due to sluggish sales 
of crude oil, and stressed again: "I would like to ask for 
understanding from Japan, to which our country owes the second 
largest amount of debts, next to France." 
  He pointed out that prospects are not optimistic for the 
debt 
issue. He said that Algeria's debt service ratio (ratio of 
foreign debt repayment to exports) reached 86 percent in fiscal 
1993, and predicted that "in 1994, the debt service ratio will 
be 90 percent or more." 
  With regard to the reasons for this, he said: "The oil 
market, (in which oil producing countries are hesitating to 
cooperate with each other in cutting oil production), is now 
falling into disorder. We cannot take an optimistic view either 
on the short-term or the long-term situation." 
  Benachenhou further stated: "I would like to invite European 
and Japanese companies to take part in the development of 
abundant deposits of LNG (liquefied natural gas) in Algeria." 

</TEXT>

