<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polls Gauge Hosokawa Cabinet Support Rate </TI></H3>
<H4>   Support Rate Drops </H4>
<F P=102> OW2103091394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2103091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to results of JIJI PRESS AGENCY's monthly 
poll revealed on 18 March, the support rate for the Hosokawa 
cabinet dropped to 49.7 percent, an 8.9-point decline compared 
with the previous survey held in February. This is the first 
time that the Hosokawa cabinet's support rate dropped below 50 
percent. The most common reason given by those interviewed in a 
survey conducted last August, when the Hosokawa administration 
was inaugurated, was that "we trust the prime minister." In the 
recent poll, however, the number of respondents who cited the 
same reason declined to 11.9 percent, showing decreasing public 
trust in the Hosokawa cabinet. 
  This is a serious situation for Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, who has been relying on the high support rate most for 
dealing with the political situation. The drop may also 
negatively affect the stalled Diet session. 
  As for political parties, support rate for the three 
coalition parties -- including the Social Democratic Party of 
Japan [SDPJ], which opposed the cabinet reshuffle and insisted 
on joining "the SDPJ, Democratic Socialist Pary, and liberal 
forces" -- grew. 
  The poll was conducted from 10 to 13 March by interviewing 
2,000 men and women and 68.9 percent of them responded. 

</TEXT>

