<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ramos Approves Central Luzon Development Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2103022294 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 17 Mar 94 pp 
1, 8 </F>

<F P=103> BK2103022294 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] President Ramos has approved a comprehensive 
development plan for Central Luzon involving the setting up of 
industrial sites and the preservation of highly protected 
farmlands in order to spur economic recovery and alleviate the 
plight of the people displaced as a result of the eruption of 
Mt. Pinatubo. 
  The president directed the members of Cabinet Cluster A and 
all the local chief executives in the provinces of Bulacan, 
Pampanga, Tarlac, Nueva Ecija, Bataan, and Zambales to 
immediately meet and draw up a land use plan which will identify 
areas suitable for industrial, residential, and agricultural 
purposes. 
  Secretary Ernesto Garilao of the Department of Agrarian 
Reform (DAR) reported yesterday that in a meeting of the Cabinet 
Cluster A last Tuesday, it was initially decided that the new 
program would be similar to the development plan for the 
Calabarzon Provinces of Cavite, Laguna, Batangas, Rizal, and 
Quezon in Southern Tagalog. 
  President Ramos, Garilao said, wants to convert Central 
Luzon 
into another economic zone capable of providing adequate food 
supply, job opportunities, and decent and affordable dwelling 
units. 
  Garilao said under the proposed land use plan, concerned 
local government units (LGUs) can promptly cite areas where 
development projects such as low cost housing and industrial 
centers can be established. 
  Likewise, it would also guide the LGUs in effectively 
preserving prime agricultural lands mostly planted to rice, 
corn, vegetables, and fruits. 
  He said the zoning plan aims principally to prevent the 
failures on effective land use earlier encountered in Calabarzon 
and involving mostly cases of unauthorized land conversion. 
  While problems cropped up in Calarbarzon because of 
non-availability of a rationale and sustainable land use plan, 
Garilao said, the development efforts, nonetheless, were proven 
a big success as reflected in the total investments poured in 
the area amounting to P [Philippine pesos] 140 billion from 1986 
to 1993. 
  During the same period the total amount of investments 
injected in Central Luzon reached only P30 billion, he said. 
  The Department of Trade and Industry has received 
commitments 
from both foreign and local capitalists to invest in Central 
Luzon, he said. 
  Garilao said Tarlac, Pampanga, and parts of Zambales and 
Bataan are among the areas where industrial sites can be set up 
while Nueva Ecija and Bulacan could very well be tapped for 
agricultural production. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6651 </DOCNO>
