<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farmers Said To Meet Seed Rice Planting Quota </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2103102194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1012 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 21 (KCNA) -- Sowing of seed rice on 
cold-frame beds began on the cooperative fields of Korea as 
spring came. 
  The cooperative farmers throughout the country have made 
full 
preparations for rice-seedling cold beds with a goal of 
harvesting another bumper crops this year marking the 30th 
anniversary of the publication of the socialist rural theses 
(February 1964). 
  Doing farming on a scientific and technological basis on the 
principle of the right crop in the right time and the right crop 
on the right soil, they set down to the sowing of seed rice on 
cold-frame beds in good time. 
  In Yonbaek, Jaeryong, Yoltusamcholli and other plain areas, 
the granaries on the west coast of the country, the first day 
sowing quotas were overfulfilled with the help of various kinds 
of highly efficient machines including seed rice sowing and 
manuring machines. 
  The cooperative farms there have more than doubled their 
work speed daily by scrupulously organizing workforce according 
to different processes of the sowing. 
  The rural communities in North Phyongan and North Hwanghae 
Provinces chose fast-growing and high-yielding strains and are 
strictly meeting the technical requirements in sowing. 
  The sowing of seed rice on cold beds takes more than ten 
days. It is a very important farming process in Korea. 
  Meanwhile, the preparation of humus-potted maize seedlings 
is 
in full swing in rural communities throughout the country. 
  The work had been carried out at 57 percent nationwide as of 
March 18. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

