<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Confirms Democracy Remarks to Li Peng </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2103131194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1251 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2103131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 21 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa confirmed Monday [21 March] that he had told Chinese 
Premier Li Peng that "it is not sensible for Western countries 
to impose their own values of democracy upon other countries." 
  Hosokawa, talking with reporters on a flight back from 
China, 
said he only spoke generally about Japan's position. He denied 
any intention of criticizing the United States which links 
improvement of China's human rights record with the renewal in 
June of its most-favored-nation (MFN) trade status. 
  Japanese officials, briefing reporters about talks between 
the Japanese and Chinese leaders at a banquet in Beijing on 
Saturday, said Hosokawa urged China to improve its human rights 
record. The officials quoted Hosokawa as saying that the 
international community recognizes human rights as a universal 
value. 
  But China's Foreign Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin offered a 
different version of Hosokawa's comment, saying the Japanese 
leader "expressed his view that it is not sensible for Western 
countries to impose their own values of democracy upon other 
countries." 
  "He also pointed out that various countries in the world 
should make joint efforts to realize the principles and spirit 
enshrined in the Declaration (on Human Rights)," Wu quoted 
Hosokawa as saying. 

</TEXT>

