<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, EU Agree on 1994 Japanese Auto Exports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903041494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0225 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903041494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 19 KYODO -- Japan and the European 
Union (EU) agreed on a 0.4% rise in Japanese car exports 
to the 
EU in 1994 from the previous year, Japanese officials said 
Saturday. 
  Japanese and European Commission trade officials set the 
level of Japanese auto exports to the trading bloc in 1994 at 
984,000 vehicles, up slightly from 980,000 for 1993, the 
officials said. The negotiations were based on a 1991 accord 
between the two sides to monitor Japanese car exports to the EU 
until the end of 1999, after which all EU restrictions on car 
imports will be lifted. 
  In the talks in late February, the European Commission 
forecast no growth in European demand for cars this year, while 
Japan is looking for a slight increase. 
  The levels set for 1993 had to be renegotiated in September 
after demand in the EU markets sank more than expected. The 
1993 target represents a drop of 18.5 0.000000rom the previous year. 

</TEXT>

