<H3> <TI>   Envoy on Wish for UN Security Council Seat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703032194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0258 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703032194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, March 16 KYODO -- Japanese Ambassador to 
the United Nations Yoshio Hatano stressed anew Wednesday [16 
March] that Japan is prepared to become a permanent member of 
the United Nations Security Council (UNSC). During a closed 
door session of the UN working group on the reform of the 
Security Council, Hatano said he is taking "this opportunity to 
emphasize once again Japan's firm determination in this regard." 
  Japanese diplomatic sources said Japan expects to have veto 
power as a permanent security council member, although Hatano 
did not elaborate on the veto issue during the meeting. 
  Hatano also proposed an increase in the number of 
nonpermanent members of the Security Council from the current 
10. The five permanent members are Britain, China, France, 
Russia and the United States. 
  Britain has joined the United States in expressing support 
for permanent UN Security Council seats for Japan and Germany. 

</TEXT>

