<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata on Need To Unify Ruling Coalition Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2103054594 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1015 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2103054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from "NHK News 7" program] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hata is now on a visit to Moscow. 
Speaking to reporters accompanying him today, he reiterated that 
it was necessary to form a completely new party through 
unification of the ruling to establish a two-party system under 
which changes of power become possible. 
  Foreign Minister Hata said: There are moves toward forming a 
new party or political alliance in the Diet. But while seeking 
appropriate ways to deal with elections to be held under the new 
electoral system, it is necessary to form a new political group 
to compete with the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP]. 
  His comments indicate he believes it is necessary to unify 
the ruling parties to establish a two-party system. 
  He was asked what he thought of the view, held by members of 
different parties within the government, that Prime Minister 
Hosokawa should lead any such new party. 
  He said: I have no objection to this idea because the prime 
minister is in charge of the government now. 
  As the deadlock in Diet interpellations is becoming 
prolonged, support is growing for the possibility of dissolving. 
Commenting on this, Hata said: Our task is to establish a 
political system which reflects people's opinions through the 
new electoral system. We are not in the position of needing to 
dissolve the Diet in the face of a host of domestic and foreign 
relations problems. 
  His comment showed he did not want the Diet dissolved under 
the current electoral system. 

</TEXT>

