<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diet Deadlock `May Delay' Tax Cuts, Recovery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903111594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1027 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 19 KYODO -- The continued stalemate in 
the Diet may delay implementation of planned tax reductions and 
further prolong Japan's recession, government officials said 
Saturday [19 March]. 
  The government plans a total of 5.85 trillion yen worth of 
cuts in income, residential and other taxes this year as 
envisaged by the latest economic stimulative package unveiled in 
early February. 
  For such reductions to be implemented on schedule as 
originally planned, the Diet would need to pass the bills by the 
end of March, according to the officials. 
  Chances are increasing, however, that some of those bills 
cannot become law on time due to a boycott of Diet business by 
the opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). 
  The LDP has refused to start deliberations on the fiscal 
1994 
budget, already two months behind schedule, over its demand that 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa clear up questions surrounding 
a 100 million yen loan he received from scandal-ridden trucking 
firm Sagawa Kyubin. 
  The LDP also maintains that the tax cuts are an important 
matter that cannot be discussed in haste. Some LDP members also 
oppose a government plan to limit the tax plan to one year. 
  The LDP stance is causing worries at the Finance Ministry. 
  Ministry officials said it takes at least two months before 
tax plans are put into practice after Diet approval because of 
the need to publicize them to companies and work out procedural 
matters. 
  If passage of the bills is delayed to mid-April, they said, 
income tax returns may not come in time for employees at 
companies which pay summer bonuses in early June. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

