Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- An influential business 
leader criticized Friday [18 March] a delay in Diet 
deliberations of the 1994 fiscal budget due to a debt problem 
involving Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Masaru Hayami, chairman of the Japan Association of 
Corporate 
Executives (Keizai Doyukai), told a news conference it is 
strange that the Diet proceeding has been held up because of an 
affair that took place 10 years ago. 
  He referred to an opposition demand that Hosokawa submit a 
detailed report on 100 million yen which he said was borrowed 
from Sagawa Kyubin trucking company. 
  Hayami's remark reflected worries in the business community 
that the stalled debate on the budget proposal may affect the 
domestic economy, which has shown signs of recovery. 

