<F P=103> OW1703070594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Imported rice may be used 
for school lunches for primary and junior-high school children 
because of a shortage of domestic rice, Japan's farm minister 
said Thursday [17 March]. 
  Eijiro Hata, minister of agriculture, forestry and 
fisheries, 
said that though the policy of the ministry's Food Agency is to 
use only Japanese rice for school meals, schools will be 
supplied with foreign rice if the principals agree to it. 
  He made the remark to the committee on agriculture, forestry 
an fisheries of the House of Councillors. 
  The Food Agency has announced that only domestic rice should 
be used for school meals, but some educators have proposed that 
use of imported rice would be of educational as well as 
nutritional value to school children by giving them a direct 
experience related to the current rice controversy. 

