<H3> <TI>   Rice Consumption Reportedly Falls in Oct-Dec </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1803122794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0959 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1803122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 18 KYODO -- Despite the recent fuss 
over a rice shortage, data shows that the trend among the 
Japanese is to consume less rice than before, the Food Agency 
said Friday [18 March]. 
  According to the agency, rice consumption in the October- 
December period in 1993 fell 0.9 percent from the same period 
the previous year to 5,458 grams per person in an ordinary 
household. 
  Households involved in rice growing were excluded. 
  In the preceding July-September period, consumption rose 0.4 
percent, going to the plus side for the first time in eight 
years. 
  "The return to the minus side is evidence that rice 
consumption is on the decline," an official at the Food Agency 
said. 
  Rice eaten at home fell 1.9 percent to 4,391 grams per 
person, while rice consumed outside of the home grew 3.3 percent 
to 1,068 grams. 

</TEXT>

