<H3> <TI>   MITI: Jan Industrial Output Rises 1.0 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703064194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0608 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703064194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Japan's industrial 
production in January grew 1.0 percent from the preceding month, 
an upward revision from a 0.9 percent rise reported earlier, the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry said Thursday [17 
March]. 
  The seasonally adjusted production index for the mining and 
manufacturing sectors stood at 88.7 against a base of 100 for 
1990. 
  The shipment index, given as 90.0, was revised up to a 0.7 
percent growth from a 0.6 percent increase in the preliminary 
report released in late February. 
  The inventory index, at 107.9, fell 0.4 percent from 
December, unchanged from the earlier report. 
  The index of the inventory-to-sales ratio, at 122.3, dropped 
2.9 percent, a revision from a 3.2 percent decrease in the 
preliminary report. 
  Before adjustments, January industrial production registered 
a revised 3.0 percent decline from a year earlier. 
  Both unadjusted shipments and inventories decreased a 
revised 
3.1 percent in January from a year ago, MITI said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

