<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North-South Contact Held on 19 Mar in Panmunjom </TI></H3>
<H4>   Businesses React to Breakdown </H4>
<F P=102> SK2103014594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0119 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 21 (YONHAP) -- South Korean businesses' 
plans for economic cooperation with the North were frustrated by 
the rupture of inter-Korean contacts on Saturday, sources said 
Monday. 
  The business community, after closely watching the 
inter-Korean contacts on exchanging special envoys in the 
expectation that they might pave the way for cross-border 
establishment of economic offices or trade representatives, was 
deeply disappointed at the rupture. 
  Large enterprises including Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo and 
Sunkyung as well as many small- and medium-sized businesses have 
already formed task forces to prepare for economic links with 
Pyongyang and have worked for more than a year to realize 
actural cooperation including joint investment in the North. 
  However, their efforts are unlikely to bear fruit for now 
after northern delegates unexpectedly walked out of the 
inter-Korean contact and in light of the South's quick shift to 
a hard-line policy. 
  One source said, "the large enterprises are expected to 
continue their processing-on-commission trade with the North for 
the time being through third countries, including China and Hong 
Kong." 
  Processing-on-commission trade involves South Korean 
businesses providing raw materials or half-finished goods to the 
North and later importing finished goods through third 
countries. But even this kind of trade may decrease with the 
deterioration of inter-Korean relations, the sources expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

