<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Rejects Kantor Request on Auto Parts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903044494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 19 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1903044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 18 March Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] At a news conference following a cabinet meeting 
held on the morning of 18 March, Hiroshi Kumagai, international 
trade and industry minister, commented on U.S. Trade 
Representative (USTR) Mickey Kantor's request to the Japanese 
Government to guarantee the realization of Japanese automakers' 
voluntary plans to import foreign-made auto parts and said: 
"The government is not in the position of being able to 
guarantee anything concerning private companies' business 
activities. We cannot accept it." He then pointed out: 
"Independent efforts by the private companies are necessary. 
Even if we decide not to accept it, the United States will 
accept our decision in its own way." As for the fact that 
Yutaka Kume, chairman of the Japan Automobile Manufacturers 
Association, criticized the stand of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI], which demands that 
private industry draw up independent plans, the minister of 
international trade and industry said, "The government is not 
in the position of giving compulsory guidance to private 
industry." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

