<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cuba Agrees To Join Data Exchange Center </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1903115094 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0749 GMT 19 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1903115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, March 19 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Cuban 
Foreign Minister Alberto Robaina Gonzales said Saturday his 
country agreed to become a member of the South Investment, Trade 
and Technology Data Exchange Centre (SITTDEC). 
  His government decided to join SITTDEC a few months ago 
after 
following SITTDEC's development since its inception about two 
years ago. 
  We were briefed about SITTDEC and its development today and 
I 
think that Cuba will benefit if it joins, he told reporters 
through an interpreter after visiting the SITTDEC office at the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry here. 
  SITTDEC, an agency of the group of 15 developing countries 
(G-15), set up through Malaysia's initiative, was adopted at the 
grouping's second summit in Caracas, Venezuela, in November 1991. 
  SITTDEC would help relay business information to member 
countries to reduce economic dependence on the developed 
countries. 
  Gonzales, who is leading a seven-member delegation, was 
earlier briefed by SITTDEC executive director Mohamed Salleh 
Masduki. 
  Cuba would be the 15th country to join SITTDEC. 
  Gonzales and his delegation arrived Saturday for a three-day 
official visit. 
  Meanwhile, Mohamed Salleh said Indonesia, India, Argentina, 
Chile, Jamaica, Senegal, Zimbabwe and Algeria were among 
countries that had joined SITTDEC. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

